message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The distended abdomen and absence of a perineal opening suggest an imperforate anus. The dark green discharge is likely meconium that is unable to pass through. Meconium ileus occurs in the small intestine, not the anus. Hirschsprung disease and colonic atresia may also present with distended abdomen, but the absence of a perineal opening points towards imperforate anus.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The presentation of a distended abdomen, flat perineal region without an opening, and a discharge from the vulva are consistent with imperforate anus, which is a failure of the anal opening to form properly. Meconium ileus, Hirschsprung disease, and colonic atresia all involve obstruction of the intestines but do not present with the same physical exam findings as imperforate anus.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The distended abdomen and flat perineal region without an opening suggests imperforate anus, and the dark green discharge coming out of the vulva indicates the presence of a fistula. Meconium ileus and colonic atresia usually present with vomiting and failure to pass meconium. Hirschsprung disease presents with constipation and failure to pass meconium.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The combination of a distended abdomen, flat perineal region without an opening, and a dark green discharge from the vulva suggests an imperforate anus. Meconium ileus and colonic atresia would present with different symptoms such as abdominal distension without a flat perineal region or discharge from the vulva. Hirschsprung disease would present with constipation and failure to pass meconium.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The newborn has a distended abdomen and a flat perineal region without an opening, which suggests a diagnosis of imperforate anus. The dark green discharge from the vulva indicates the presence of a rectovaginal fistula, a common associated anomaly. Meconium ileus and colonic atresia are not associated with the absence of an anal opening. Hirschsprung disease may cause constipation and distention, but there will be an anal opening present.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The presenting symptoms of a distended abdomen and lack of anal opening indicate imperforate anus, which can lead to the discharge of meconium through the vulva. Meconium ileus is a blockage in the small intestine due to the presence of abnormally thick meconium, while Hirschsprung disease and colonic atresia involve abnormalities in the colon, but do not present with a lack of anal opening.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The distended abdomen and the absence of the anal opening suggest that this newborn has an imperforate anus. The dark green discharge coming from the vulva is due to the passage of meconium through the vagina. Meconium ileus and colonic atresia are not associated with an absence of the anal opening. Hirschsprung disease may cause constipation and abdominal distension, but the absence of the anal opening rules out this diagnosis.

We refer to the Merck Manual for help. The most likely diagnosis is Imperforate anus as there is a flat perineal region without an opening and a dark green discharge coming out of the vulva. Meconium ileus is associated with cystic fibrosis, Hirschsprung disease is associated with failure to pass meconium within 48 hours of birth, and colonic atresia is associated with abdominal distension and vomiting.

The dark green discharge coming out of the vulva is due to the passage of meconium through the genitourinary tract. Meconium ileus, Hirschsprung disease, and colonic atresia have different presentations and are not consistent with the given symptoms.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The newborn's presentation with distended abdomen, absence of anal opening, and green discharge from the vulva indicates an imperforate anus. Meconium ileus would present with abdominal distention, vomiting, and failure to pass meconium stool. Hirschsprung disease would present with failure to pass stool or passage of ribbon-like stools. Colonic atresia would present with failure to pass stool and abdominal distension.
